Hence if any one, not thinking to swear, utters the words of an oath‚ it is not swearing. See in Ovid the story of Cydippe, [who read aloud on an apple which Acontius her lover had thrown at her, I swear that I will marry Acontius] So Euripides in the Hip- polytus.

But if any one, willingly swearing, wished not to bind himself, he is not the less obliged, because obligation is the necessary effect of an oath, and inseparable from it.
